ays&rsquo; notice of any hearing.</p>\n\n<h2>Hearings</h2>\n\n<p>The hearing will usually be held in the area covered by the police force which investigated the crime.</p>\n\n<p>The hearing will be attended by:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>2 or 3 tribunal judges or members</li>\n  <li>a clerk</li>\n  <li>a representative from the <abbr title=\"Criminal Injuries Compensation Authority\">CICA</abbr></li>\n  <li>any witnesses</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>A police officer who knows about your case may also attend if they can help the tribunal.</p>\n\n<p>Offenders don&rsquo;t usually attend tribunal hearings.</p>\n\n<h2>What happens at a hearing</h2>\n\n<p>You will be asked questions about the crime and your injuries.</p>\n\n<p>Other witnesses will only come into the hearing room to give evidence, and will then leave.</p>\n\n<p>You or your representative can ask questions during the hearing, and can make points at the end.</p>\n\n<p>You will usually get the tribunal&rsquo;s decision on the day of the hearing.</p>\n\n<h2>Expenses for going to the hearing</h2>\n\n<p>The tribunal will send you information on how to claim expenses for going to the hearing, such as travel costs.</p>\n\n"},{"web_url":"https://www.gov.uk/criminal-injuries-compensation-tribunal/if-you-lose-your-appeal","slug":"if-you-lose-your-appeal","order":4,"title":"If you lose your appeal","body":"<p>The tribunal&rsquo;s decision is final.</p>\n\n<p>You may be able to ask for a &lsquo;judicial review&rsquo; of the decision if you think the decision was wrong for a legal reason.</p>\n\n<p>If you&rsquo;re unsure about this, you can get <a rel=\"external\" href=\"http://legaladviserfinder.justice.gov.uk/AdviserSearch.do\" title=\"legal advice\">legal advice.</a></p>\n\n<p>Before applying for a judicial review:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>write to the tribunal, saying why you think the decision was wrong</li>\n  <li>ask for written reasons for its decision</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>You must do this within 1 month of the date of the decision.</p>\n\